{"id":"palisades-scenic-byway","generatedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z","designation":"National Scenic Byway","parkCode":null,"source":{"roadArticle":"Palisades Interstate Parkway","revisionId":1335552793,"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Palisades_Interstate_Parkway"},"attribution":{"license":"CC BY-SA 4.0","licenseUrl":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","articleUrl":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Palisades_Interstate_Parkway","text":"Route, junction, and history details adapted from the Wikipedia article \"Palisades Interstate Parkway\", by Wikipedia contributors, licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0."},"sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia","src":"wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Palisades_Interstate_Parkway","revisionId":1335552793,"retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z"},{"name":"Federal Highway Administration — National Scenic Byways","src":"fhwa","url":"https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways","retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z"},{"name":"OpenStreetMap contributors (ODbL)","src":"osm","url":"https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright","retrievedAt":"2026-07-10T18:35:17.820Z"}],"endpoints":{"from":"Fort Lee, NJ","to":"Bear Mountain State Park, NJ","via":["Sparkill, NJ","West Nyack, NJ","Pomona, NJ"]},"itinerary":[{"seq":1,"place":"Fort Lee","state":"NJ","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":0,"toNextMi":1.9,"note":"The drive begins here","control":["New York City","Hudson Terrace","Fort Lee","Gas stations (one on each side","no crossover)"],"lat":41.31518,"lng":-74.01604,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":2,"place":"Englewood Cliffs","state":"NJ","kind":"town","mileFromStart":1.9,"toNextMi":3.5,"note":"Junction toward Englewood Cliffs & Englewood","control":["Englewood Cliffs","Englewood","Rockefeller Lookout (northbound side only)"],"lat":41.00472,"lng":-73.91988,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":3,"place":"Alpine","state":"NJ","kind":"town","mileFromStart":5.4,"toNextMi":7.4,"note":"Junction toward Alpine Lookout (northbound side only)","control":["Alpine Lookout (northbound side only)","Alpine","Closter","Palisades Interstate Park Commission Visitor Center & State Line Lookout","Sparkill","NY","Piermont"],"lat":41.00472,"lng":-73.91988,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":4,"place":"Sparkill","state":"NJ","kind":"town","mileFromStart":12.8,"toNextMi":0.7,"note":"Junction toward Sparkill Service Area","control":["Sparkill Service Area"],"lat":41.02689,"lng":-73.93767,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":5,"place":"Tappan","state":"NJ","kind":"town","mileFromStart":13.5,"toNextMi":0.9,"note":"Junction toward Orangeburg & Tappan","control":["Orangeburg","Tappan"],"lat":null,"lng":null,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":6,"place":"Orangeburg","state":"NJ","kind":"town","mileFromStart":14.4,"toNextMi":2.8,"note":"Junction toward Orangeburg & Pearl River","control":["Orangeburg","Pearl River"],"lat":null,"lng":null,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":7,"place":"West Nyack","state":"NJ","kind":"town","mileFromStart":17.2,"toNextMi":3.2,"note":"Junction toward Nanuet & West Nyack","control":["Nanuet","West Nyack","Nyack","Spring Valley","White Plains","New York City","Albany"],"lat":41.08736,"lng":-73.98957,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":8,"place":"New City","state":"NJ","kind":"town","mileFromStart":20.4,"toNextMi":2.1,"note":"Junction toward New City & Nanuet","control":["New City","Nanuet"],"lat":null,"lng":null,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":9,"place":"New Hempstead","state":"NJ","kind":"town","mileFromStart":22.5,"toNextMi":2.7,"note":"Junction toward New City & New Square","control":["New City","New Square","New Hempstead","Spring Valley"],"lat":41.15055,"lng":-74.02551,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":10,"place":"Pomona","state":"NJ","kind":"town","mileFromStart":25.2,"toNextMi":2.3,"note":"Junction toward Pomona & Haverstraw","control":["Pomona","Haverstraw","Suffern"],"lat":41.00472,"lng":-73.91988,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":11,"place":"Stony Point","state":"NJ","kind":"town","mileFromStart":27.5,"toNextMi":2.4,"note":"Junction toward West Haverstraw","control":["West Haverstraw","Stony Point"],"lat":null,"lng":null,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":12,"place":"Harriman State Park","state":"NJ","kind":"park-entrance","mileFromStart":29.9,"toNextMi":4.7,"note":"Junction toward Lake Welch & Sebago Beach","control":["Lake Welch","Sebago Beach","Palisades Interstate Park Commission Visitor Center","Anthony Wayne Recreation Area","Central Valley"],"lat":null,"lng":null,"src":"wikipedia"},{"seq":13,"place":"Bear Mountain State Park","state":"NJ","kind":"terminus","mileFromStart":34.6,"toNextMi":null,"note":"The drive ends here","control":["Bear Mountain State Park","Fort Montgomery","West Point","Peekskill","Haverstraw"],"lat":41.00472,"lng":-73.91988,"src":"wikipedia"}],"history":{"paragraphs":["In 1933–34, the first thoughts of a Palisades Interstate Parkway were developed by engineer and environmentalist William A. Welch, who was general manager and chief engineer of the Palisades Interstate Park Commission. The plan was to build a parkway to connect the New Jersey Palisades with the state parks along the Hudson River in Rockland and Orange counties. Welch would soon garner the support of John D. Rockefeller, who donated 700 acres (2.8 km2) of land along the New Jersey Palisades overlooking the Hudson River in 1933. With this favorable momentum for the new route, the proposed route was accepted as a Civil Works Administration project under Franklin D. Roosevelt's New Deal coalition. However, the New Jersey Highway Commission did not support construction, so the idea of a parkway was put on hold. Instead, they built an 8 miles (13 km) road along the western bank of the Hudson River called the Henry Hudson Drive, a small scenic road that is a precursor to the Parkway and is still open today.","During the 1940s, Rockefeller renewed the push for a parkway along the New Jersey Palisades, and teamed with ultimate PIP planner, Robert Moses, to establish and design the parkway. The plan originally was to have the PIP stretch from the Garden State Parkway, along the Hudson River, to the George Washington Bridge, and then north along its present-day route ending at the Bear Mountain Bridge. This southern extension was never built, but construction began on the current PIP in New York on April 1, 1947. Construction on the New Jersey portion began about one year later, paralleling the nearby Henry Hudson Drive. Construction was delayed twice due to material shortages, but that did not stop the PIP from being opened in stages during the 1940s and 1950s. The route was completed in New Jersey in 1957, and on August 28, 1958, the final piece of the PIP was completed between exits 5 and 9 in southern Rockland County.","The PIP is known for its stone arch overpasses throughout its route and its several scenic overlooks in New Jersey. All sorts of unique trees and flowers can be seen along the route as well. In 1998, because of all the natural and constructed beauty, the PIP was designated as a national landmark by the National Park Service.","The Parkway suffered from severe flooding and a minor structural collapse on July 9, 2023, near the Bear Mountain Bridge as a result of severe storms."],"sourceSection":"History","src":"wikipedia"},"highlights":[{"n":"Fort Lee","d":"The drive begins here","q":"Fort Lee","lat":40.85064,"lng":-73.971007,"src":"wikipedia"},{"n":"Bear Mountain State Park","d":"The drive ends here","q":"Bear Mountain State Park","lat":41.31277778,"lng":-74.00583333,"src":"wikipedia"}],"references":[{"n":1,"text":"\"NJ Route 445 Straight Line Diagram\" (PDF). New Jersey Department of Transportation. May 2010. Retrieved March 17, 2020.","url":"http://www.state.nj.us/transportation/refdata/sldiag/pdf/00000445__-.pdf"},{"n":2,"text":"\"2007 Traffic Data Report for New York State\" (PDF). New York State Department of Transportation. July 25, 2008. Retrieved July 17, 2009.","url":"https://www.dot.ny.gov/divisions/engineering/technical-services/hds-respository/Traffic%20Data%20Report%202007.pdf"},{"n":3,"text":"Staff. \"PALISADES ROUTE WILL OPEN TODAY; Officials to Mark Completion of Final Link in 42-Mile Interstate Parkway\", The New York Times, August 28, 1958. Accessed April 7, 2016. \"The final gap in a scenic route overlooking the Hudson River will be closed with a ceremony at noon to","url":"https://www.nytimes.com/1958/08/28/archives/palisades-route-will-open-today-officials-to-mark-completion-of.html"},{"n":4,"text":"\"TITLE 16. DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION - CHAPTER 32. TRUCK ACCESS\" (PDF). New Jersey Department of Transportation. Archived from the original (PDF) on September 20, 2008. Retrieved August 13, 2010.","url":"https://web.archive.org/web/20080920214137/http://www.state.nj.us/transportation/about/rules/pdf/chapter32truckaccess.pdf"},{"n":5,"text":"\"New York Parkway truck restriction brochure\" (PDF). New York City Department of Transportation and New York State Department of Transportation. Retrieved July 31, 2012.","url":"http://www.nyc.gov/html/dot/downloads/pdf/trucks_nycarea_parkways.pdf"},{"n":6,"text":"\"NJ Route 445S Straight Line Diagram\" (PDF). New Jersey Department of Transportation. May 2010. Retrieved February 5, 2012.","url":"http://www.state.nj.us/transportation/refdata/sldiag/00000445S_-.pdf"},{"n":7,"text":"\"NJDOT to begin Palisades Parkway repaving project\" (Press release). NJDOT. July 17, 2014. Retrieved July 28, 2014.","url":"http://www.state.nj.us/transportation/about/press/2014/071714.shtm"},{"n":8,"text":"New York State Department of Transportation (January 2012). Official Description of Highway Touring Routes, Bicycling Touring Routes, Scenic Byways, & Commemorative/Memorial Designations in New York State (PDF). Retrieved February 5, 2012.","url":"https://www.dot.ny.gov/divisions/operating/oom/transportation-systems/repository/2012%20tour-bk.pdf"}],"routeLine":[[41.31518,-74.01604],[41.31456,-74.01636],[41.31399,-74.01679],[41.31348,-74.01734],[41.31302,-74.01799],[41.31266,-74.0187],[41.31238,-74.0195],[41.31215,-74.02032],[41.31188,-74.02